Title:
No Agent, No Problem: Discovering Remote EDR

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post shows how to build “agentless” endpoint monitoring by remotely enumerating and creating ETW trace sessions using Windows Performance Logs and Alerts (PLA) DCOM/COM interfaces (pla.dll), rather than deploying an EDR agent or using WMI.  
- It explains PLA concepts (data collectors, data collector sets, namespaces) and how tools like `logman` use `IDataCollectorSetCollection::GetDataCollectorSets` and related interfaces to query across namespaces, including less-visible ones (e.g., Service namespace vs Session).  
- The author demonstrates remote creation/modification of collectors via `IDataCollectorSet` + `Commit()` (with server parameter for remote targets) and highlights XML-templated collector creation (`CreateDataCollectorFromXml`) as a practical approach for trace collectors.  
- A PoC tool, JonMon-Lite, is presented to create remote trace sessions from XML/JSON config, write ETL output to a chosen location (including “remote host collects, local host stores”), and parse/forward events into local Event Viewer for analysis.  
- Defensive examples include detecting .NET assembly loads, Permanent WMI Event Subscriptions, and DCSync activity via relevant ETW providers (e.g., DotNETRuntime, WMI-Activity, RPC).  
- Offensive implications include stealthy remote recon/telemetry collection, hiding sessions in non-default namespaces, and remotely stopping/modifying security trace sessions (e.g., changing providers or security descriptors).  
- Useful for detection engineers and defenders seeking visibility without endpoint agents, and for red teams researching stealthy monitoring and ETW/PLA abuse paths.

Technical Focus:
- ETW remote collection via PLA (pla.dll) DCOM interfaces  
- IDataCollectorSet / IDataCollectorSetCollection / IDataCollector COM API usage  
- Data collector namespaces (Session, Service, AutoLogger, etc.) and enumeration gaps  
- Remote creation/modification of trace sessions using `Commit()` and `CommitMode`  
- XML-templated trace collector provisioning (`CreateDataCollectorFromXml`)  
- Authentication/credentialing for remote collection and remote/local ETL storage

Use Cases:
- Agentless remote telemetry collection on servers/endpoints where EDR agents are undesirable
- Distributed ETW-based detection pipeline (ETL collection + near-real-time parsing/forwarding)
- Remote hunting for suspicious activity using targeted ETW providers (RPC, WMI-Activity, .NET runtime)
- Red-team stealth monitoring/recon without dropping binaries to disk
- Auditing and hardening: detect/alert on unexpected PLA collector creation or trace session tampering

Keywords:
ETW, Performance Logs and Alerts, PLA, pla.dll, DCOM, COM, IDataCollectorSet, IDataCollectorSetCollection, IDataCollector, ITraceDataCollector, IConfigurationDataCollector, logman, PerfMon, Data Collector Set, namespace, AutoLogger, ETL, CommitMode, CreateDataCollectorFromXml, Microsoft-Windows-DotNETRuntime, Microsoft-Windows-WMI-Activity, Microsoft-Windows-RPC, DCSync, Mimikatz, Rubeus